/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the context of an environmental crisis, photography and its related practices can be part of an emancipatory project, challenging techno-utopian solutions and envisioning alternative possibilities for sustaining life on this planet. This anthology critically addresses the geopolitics of environmental devastation from the perspective of photographers, artists, curators and theorists. The contributors engage with recent debates about the Anthropocene and the need to identify the socioeconomic and political causes of climate change. The essays question the validity of images within which ecological crisis is seen as the consequence of undifferentiated human activity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 4aArt History. 4aArt. 4aClimate. 4aFine Arts. 4aGeopolitics. 4aHuman Ecology. 4aImage. 4aLandscape. 4aNature. 4aNorthern. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh  aArt History.  aArt.  aClimate.  aFine Arts.  aGeopolitics.  aHuman Ecology.  aImage.  aLandscape.  aNature.  aNorthern.1 aBartlett, Flora Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrenzel, Janna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldie, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldie, Chris, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHartle, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvard, Jonas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvey, Aileen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHyvönen, Mats, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarit Waade, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1